    What is event driven MicroServices architecture(EDA)
EDA is a software design pattern in which decoupled applications can
asynchronously publish and subscribe to events via an event broker/message broker.

In EDA, applications communicate with each-other by sending and receiving events or message.
EDA is often referred to as "Asynchronous communication"

    How EDA works and what is it advantages
In EDA, we create multiple micro services
And we use a message broker as a messaging system for asynchronous communication between multiple micro services
    Advantages of EDA
-Improves Flexibility and Maintainability: each service do a specific thing and they are independent.
-High Scalability: You can just create another service that will start consuming the event from the message broker without interfering with other services.
-It improves the availability: If one micro service goes down, it wont affect others.

    Install and setup kafka on windows
search - apache kafka download
https://kafka.apache.org/quickstart/
-After unzipping
-cd to the kafka folder
    step 1 - Generate a Cluster UUID
bin\windows\kafka-storage.bat random-uuid
-Format Log Directories
bin\windows\kafka-storage.bat format --standalone -t CLUSTER_ID -c config/server.properties
    step 2 - Start the Kafka Server
bin\windows\kafka-server-start.bat config/server.properties
Once the Kafka server has successfully launched, you will have a basic Kafka environment running and ready to use.
    step 3 - Create a topic to store your events
.\ represents current directory
.\bin\windows\kafka-topics.bat --create --topic topic-example --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
    step 4 - Write some events into the topic
.\bin\windows\kafka-console-producer.bat --topic topic-example --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
 >Hello world
 >kafka topic event
 >demo 1
 >demo2
 ctrl + c to exist
    step 5 consume/Read the event from the kafka topic
.\bin\windows\kafka-console-consumer.bat --topic topic-example --from-beginning --bootstrap-server localhost:9092